    <chapter xml:id="ch_intro">
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <p>
        We'll start with Euclid. Euclid was a greek mathematician living about  600 BC. His book, Elements, still serves as a foundation for modern geometry.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will assume you are familiar with the basic concepts of geometry, such as points, lines, planes and solids. We will further assume the ideas of length and angle are familiar.
      </p>
      <p> 
        Implicit in Euclid's Elements is a three-dimensional space, now called Euclidean space. It corresponds the physical space around us. Its qualities:
        <ul>
          <li>Three-dimensions</li>
          <li> Orthogonal axes</li>
          <li>x,y,z; i,j,k</li>
          <li>metric, dot product</li>
        </ul>
      </p>

<p>
        A vector is a quantity with magnitude and direction. A scalar is a quantity with magnitude only.
       </p>

      <p> Vector quantities have two characteristics, a magnitude and a direction. Scalar quantities have only a magnitude.
        https://www.grc.nasa.gov/www/k-12/airplane/vectors.html
      </p>
      <p> 
        Vectors can be represented by directed line segments. The length of the line represents the magnitude. The direction of the line represents the direction.

      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Scalars</term> have magnitude. <term>Vectors</term> have magnitude and direction.</p>

